@flexiarg peeragogy/creating-a-guide
@title Build the Guide While You Build the Practice
@keywords handbook, map, knowledge-cartography, meaning-making, micro-map, reflexivity
@audience peer-learning practitioners, would-be authors
@tone reflective
@style process-pattern
@references [peeragogy/pattern-language peeragogy/wrapper peeragogy/discerning-a-pattern]

! conclusion: When a peer-learning practice is new, the meanings that would let participants use it are not yet stable — often they have not been created.  Writing a guide is not a separate step that follows the practice; it is part of the practice, a way of figuring out how the system works while making it more usable for the next person.  The guide is best treated as a living micro-map, edited reflexively as the territory shifts.
  + context: New practices, including peer-learning practices, accumulate tacit knowledge faster than they accumulate vocabulary.  A guide written too late is a record of a stabilised practice; a guide written in parallel is itself a tool of stabilisation.  Knowledge cartography (concept maps, glossaries, navigations) and meaning-making frames help, but the central move is reflexivity: each guide-writing pass surfaces what has been figured out, and each practice pass surfaces what the guide must update.  The handbook itself is an instance of this pattern.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: capture-now ↔ stabilise-first.
    Real: writing a guide for a moving practice risks fixing too early what should still flex; waiting for stability risks losing the stage at which the practice could have been made teachable.  Both risks operate continuously.
    Irreducible: a guide cannot simultaneously be a definitive reference and a working notebook.  The question is which mode the current pass is operating in, not whether one mode is correct.
    Active: the pull recurs at every iteration boundary — every time the practice shifts, the guide either lags, leads, or co-evolves.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Co-evolution: the guide is updated each time the practice changes substantively, with explicit dating of which sections describe which version of the practice.  Readers can see the trail.
    (2) Micro-map per activity: rather than one definitive guide, the project produces small, scoped guides for individual activities (refining a pattern, running a session, onboarding a contributor).  Each micro-map can be revised without disturbing the others.
    (3) Reflexive note: when the guide-writer notices that writing a section is forcing the practice to clarify, they record that fact in the guide itself.  The guide then documents not only the practice but the practice-of-clarifying-the-practice.
    (4) "Map is not the territory" hedge: the guide states explicitly which decisions remain open, which examples are illustrative versus prescriptive, and where the practice is still discovering itself.  Readers do not mistake provisional articulation for settled doctrine.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: the guide is updated within the same iteration as the practice changes it describes, and contributors treat editing the guide as part of doing the work.  Failing when: the guide describes a stage the project has already left, or guide-writing is treated as a separate, post-hoc job.
  + ABSENCE-SIGNALS:
    - Stale handbook: the guide describes the practice as it was at a previous version, with no dating to flag the gap.
    - Single-author bottleneck: only one person edits the guide, so guide-updates lag every change made by anyone else.
    - Premature canonicalisation: the guide is written as a definitive reference before the practice has stabilised, freezing decisions that should still be moving.
    - Tacit-knowledge accumulation: practitioners share understanding informally and never feel pressure to write it down, leaving newcomers without a path in.
